{{Infobox writer | name = Mao Samnang | embed = | honorific_prefix = | honorific_suffix = | image = | image_size = | image_upright = | alt = | caption = | native_name = | native_name_lang = | pseudonym = Rabbit | birth_name = | birth_date = <!-- {{Birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> | birth_place = | death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> | death_place = | resting_place = | occupation = Writer | language = | nationality = [[Cambodia]]n | ethnicity = | citizenship = | education = | alma_mater = | period = | genre = <!-- or: | genres = --> | subject = <!-- or: | subjects = --> | movement = | notableworks = <!-- or: | notablework = --> | spouse = <!-- or: | spouses = --> | partner = <!-- or: | partners = --> | children = | relatives = | awards = | signature = | signature_alt = | years_active = 1981 - present | module = | website = <!-- {{URL|example.org}} --> | portaldisp = <!-- "on", "yes", "true", etc; or omit --> }}
'''Mao Samnang''' is a Cambodian author who has written stories for films such as ''[[The Weird Villa]]'', ''[[The Snake King's Child]]'' and ''[[The Haunted House (2005 film)|The Haunted House]]''. She is considered to be one of the country's most popular authors.<ref>''Modern Short Fiction of Southeast Asia: A Literary History'', Teri Shaffer Yamada - [https://books.google.com/books?id=1j8LAQAAMAAJ&q=%22Mao+Samnang%22&dq=%22Mao+Samnang%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjSm7f8vo_SAhUGmpQKHVGABaAQ6AEIKTAD Page 125]</ref><ref>''Le Cambodge'', By Soizick Crochet - [https://books.google.com/books?id=EAAznFz3OoMC&pg=PA243&dq=%22Mao+Samnang%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjSm7f8vo_SAhUGmpQKHVGABaAQ6AEIHjAB#v=onepage&q=%22Mao%20Samnang%22&f=false Page 243]</ref>
==Background== Samnang started her writing around 1981. By 2016 she had more than 100 of her novels published. According to her, many of her novels have a message in them. The messages were aimed at the youth to remind or educate them about what comes of drug use.<ref>''[[Khmer Times]]'', Wednesday, 27 July 2016 - [http://www.khmertimeskh.com/news/27714/khmer-novels-endangered-as-readership-dries-up/ Khmer Novels Endangered as Readership Dries Up - Va Sonyka]</ref> Around 2009, she was earning around US$500 for each novel which took about a month to write.<ref>''[[The Phnom Penh Post]]'', Mon, 18 May 2009 - [http://www.phnompenhpost.com/lifestyle/reading-novel-obsession-among-cambodian-youth Reading: a novel obsession among Cambodian youth - Lim Seang Heng]</ref> As a screenwriter, the films she has scripted for are seen regularly around [[Phnom Penh]].<ref>''[[The Cambodia Daily]]'', June 26, 2003 - [https://www.cambodiadaily.com/archives/some-screenwriters-claim-govt-censorship-30006/ Some Screenwriters Claim Gov’t Censorship by Thet Sambath]</ref>
==Film== One of her stories put to film was Snaker, released in 2001. It was Directed by Fai Sam Ang and starred Winai Kraibutr, Pich Chanbormey, Tep Rindaro, and Om Portevy.<ref>[[Letterboxd]] - [https://letterboxd.com/film/snaker/crew/ Snaker 2001 ‘งูเก็งกอง’ Directed by Fai Sam Ang, Crew]</ref><ref>Letterboxd - [https://letterboxd.com/film/snaker/ Snaker 2001 ‘งูเก็งกอง’ Directed by Fai Sam Ang, Cast]</ref>
==Later years== Samnang Samnang stopped writing around 2014. This was due to her not being able to get a publishing deal that would allow her to write for Khmer readers. Another reason was because of problems with copyright violations.<ref>''Khmer Times'', Wednesday, 27 July 2016 - [http://www.khmertimeskh.com/news/27714/khmer-novels-endangered-as-readership-dries-up/ Khmer Novels Endangered as Readership Dries Up - Va Sonyka]</ref>
